tland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, City of Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Skotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1265–1317":"1265–1317","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1260–1330":"1260–1330","1290–1372":"1290–1372","1312–1346":"1312–1346","1314–Male":"1314–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1245–Female":"1245–Overleden","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1372":"1372","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","after 1317":"na 1317","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","about 1314":"circa 1314","1265":"1265","about 1312":"circa 1312","1317":"1317","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, City of Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1265–1317":"1265–1317","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1260–1330":"1260–1330","1290–1372":"1290–1372","1312–1346":"1312–1346","1314–Male":"1314–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1372":"1372","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","after 1317":"after 1317","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","about 1314":"about 1314","1265":"1265","about 1312":"about 1312","1317":"1317","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Abbey of Holyrood, Edinburgh, City of Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herring","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London), Dutch, and German: metonymic occupational name for a herring fisher or for a seller of the fish, or perhaps for someone who habitually ate herring, from Middle English <i>hering</i> (Old English <i>hǣring</i>, <i>hēring</i>), Dutch <i>haring</i>, Middle High German <i>hærinc</i>. In some cases it may have been a nickname in the sense of a trifle, something of little value, a meaning which is found in medieval phrases and proverbial expressions such as ‘to like neither herring nor barrel’, i.e. not to like something at all.","German: habitational name from Herringen in Westphalia.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Hering  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hearing","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Herring  .","Americanized form of German <b>Häring</b> (see   Haring  ) or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Herrin","meanings":["English: variant of   Herring  .","French: rare variant of   Herin  ."]},{"name":"Herrig","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places called Herrig in the Rhineland or from Herringen in Westphalia. See also   Herring  ."]},{"name":"Hering","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hasso, Alfons, Alois, Arno, Ernst, Erwin, Florian, Gerhard, Guenther, Kurt, Ludwig, Manfred.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>hærinc</i> ‘herring’, German <i>Hering</i>, a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, particularly a seller of herrings, or a nickname for someone supposedly resembling a herring. In some cases the Jewish surname is artificial. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the German and Jewish variant <b>Häring</b>. Compare   Haring  .","German and Dutch: habitational name from any of several places and farmhouses so named, for instance near Zeesse in Overijssel, originally inhabited by a certain <i>Here</i> or <i>Hero</i> and his kin. <i>Here</i> or <i>Hero</i> is a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name with the element <i>heri</i> ‘army’."]}]},{"name":"Giles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Much altered English vernacular form of the Late Latin name <i>Aegidius</i>, from Greek <i>Aigidios</i> (a derivative of <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’), via Old French <i>Gide</i>. It was the name of an 8th‐century saint who, according to tradition, was an Athenian citizen who fled to Provence because he could not cope with the fame and adulation caused by his power to work miracles, in particular by healing the lame and crippled. This was not a particularly common name in the Middle Ages and its use seems to have been confined to certain families and localities."],"variants":[{"name":"Gyles","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Giles ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Giles Herring was born in 1265, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, her father, Sir John Herring of Edmonstone - Lord of Gilmerton, Drum and Goodtrees, was 25 and her mother, Clarissy Nye, was 20. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Walter de Sommerville of Linton and Carnwath. She died in 1317, in Edinburgh, Scotland, at the age of 52, and was buried in Edinburgh, Scotland."},"et":{"1265–1317":"1265–1317","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1260–1330":"1260–1330","1290–1372":"1290–1372","1312–1346":"1312–1346","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1372":"1372","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","after 1317":"pärast 1317","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1265":"1265","about 1312":"umbes 1312","1317":"1317","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, S